{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645181"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.07,0.47,0.37,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10806"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96547"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9938"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25160"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25162"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin provides an essential barrier that prevents water loss and protects against environmental threats. This barrier function primarily occurs in the outermost layer of the epidermis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main structural components that create the skin barrier?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Langerhans cells and merkel cells","Dermal fibroblasts and ground substance","Keratin-filled corneocytes and intercellular lipids","Melanocytes and keratinocytes","Collagen fibres and elastin"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skin barrier is primarily formed by \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratin-filled corneocytes and intercellular lipids\u003C/strong\u003E arranged in a \u0027brick and mortar\u0027 pattern. The corneocytes are dead keratinocytes filled with keratin protein that provide mechanical strength, while the surrounding lipids create a waterproof seal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollagen fibres and elastin\u003C/strong\u003E are structural components of the dermis rather than the epidermal barrier. \u003Cstrong\u003EMelanocytes and keratinocytes\u003C/strong\u003E do not directly form the barrier structure, although keratinocytes eventually become corneocytes, while melanocytes are not directly involved in barrier function. \u003Cstrong\u003EDermal fibroblasts and ground substance\u003C/strong\u003E are components of the dermis that do not contribute to the primary barrier function. \u003Cstrong\u003ELangerhans cells and merkel cells\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised cells involved in immune function and touch sensation respectively, rather than barrier function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe arrangement of corneocytes and lipids, along with tight junctions in the stratum granulosum, creates an effective barrier against water loss and external threats while allowing the skin to remain flexible.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The stratum corneum consists of dead keratinocytes filled with keratin protein and surrounded by lipids.","The skin barrier function depends on both protein-rich corneocytes and intercellular lipids arranged in a \u0027brick and mortar\u0027 pattern.","Tight junctions in the stratum granulosum provide additional barrier function by preventing paracellular movement of substances."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 25.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96547"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96547"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T15:32:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T15:32:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10806"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attribut